{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521890"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:38:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:38:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13765"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13765"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.37,0.52,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6385"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90187"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6385"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13765"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74432"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"272"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"6511"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12416"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18092"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30607"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90187"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic for follow-up two weeks after being treated conservatively in hospital for a spontaneous pneumothorax. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination today, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Respiratory examination is unremarkable with equal air entry both sides. A follow-up chest X-ray today shows no residual pneumothorax. He is due to travel overseas in two days.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice regarding air travel?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["He may fly immediately after sustaining a pneumothorax","He should not fly for at least one week post pneumothorax resolution","He should not fly for at least four weeks post pneumothorax resolution","He should not fly for at least 12 months post pneumothorax resolution","He should never fly again"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECurrent guidelines recommend that patients should not \u003Cstrong\u003Efly for at least one week\u003C/strong\u003E after radiographic resolution of a pneumothorax. This is because of the risk of recurrence due to pressure changes during flight. The risk of pneumothorax is increased at altitude and during decompression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of a pneumothorax is an absolute contraindication to flying as the trapped air will expand at altitude and this increases the risk of complications or tension pneumothorax. Therefore, it would be considered unsafe to fly \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmediately \u003C/strong\u003E. However, there is no evidence that patients need to avoid flying for \u003Cstrong\u003Efour weeks\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003E12 months\u003C/strong\u003E after resolution.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients do not need to avoid flying indefinitely (\u003Cstrong\u003Enever fly again\u003C/strong\u003E) after a single spontaneous pneumothorax however a recurrent pneumothorax provides a higher risk of recurrence with flying and may require specialist clearance to fly.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients should not fly for at least one week after radiographic resolution of a pneumothorax.","Trapped gas will expand at increased altitudes, increasing risk of complications from a pneumothorax."],"references":["Agency for Clinical Innovation. Spontaneous pneumothorax [Internet]. New South Wales: Emergency Care Institute;. Available at https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/networks/eci/clinical/tools/respiratory/spontaneous-pneumothorax"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74432"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13765"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74432"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-12T18:28:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-12T18:29:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6385"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90187"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":